The paper describes a programming approach that involves specifying object protocols and using a high-level synchronization abstraction to synchronize methods with the states of the receiver object. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category. Additionally, the paper focuses on implementing objects with state-sensitive interfaces, which is a common concern in Software Engineering (cs.SE). The paper also discusses the use of behavioral types to specify object protocols, which is a topic that falls under the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The use of synchronization logic and the integration of protocol conformance verification suggest that the paper may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) and Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-categories.
